Preface

Over the following chapters, we will learn a bit about the analysis of the data we collect and study. We will learn to manipulate the data to make it ready for analysis and to gain insights into our data with biostatistics and machine learning methods. Our primary tool to accomplish this will be the statistical and programming language, R.

We will adopt a very practical approach. We will not emphasize abstract mathematics. Rather we will set up a number of problems coming from medical, microbiological and other areas of research and develop the knowledge necessary to solve them. At the conclusion of the course, you will have had many opportunities to apply the techniques we will develop to problems that interest you.

Let me emphasize that all the course material, including this course notebook and the presentation slides, are being prepared from within the RStudio environment, using the R Markdown format. R, together with RStudio, has a very wide range of resources. This course will only be able to scratch the surface of what the combination can do.

When the chapters include R programming, I will use the following typeface (font).

    sub_data <- data %>% 
      select(day20:day25)
    glimpse(sub_data)
    summary(sub_data)
    sub_data %>% map_dbl(sd)

At times, there will be an important point that doesn’t fit cleanly in the flow of the text, but is important to understand. I call this type of point a VSS, a verbum sapientibus satis, Latin for “a word to the wise is sufficient” in honor of Ms. Walden, my first Latin teacher in junior high school.

History of R and Why We Need It

History

Bell Labs, the former research arm of ATT in New Jersey (now owned by Nokia), was a rich source of computer languages. C and its derivatives come from there. S, a Bell Labs product of the 1970s and 1980s is a language that allowed scientists to solve statistical problems without having to write their own code for the procedures, as they would have had to do in Fortran, Cobol, Pascal or C. When ATT divested itself of Bell Labs, in the 1980s, S became a commercial product and still exists.

In the 1990s, Ross Ihaka and Robert Gentlemen, working in New Zealand, created a open-source derivative of S, that they called “R”, continuing the Bell Labs tradition of giving its languages names of one letter. Ihaka and Gentlemen, working with a group of European and American statisticians that formed themselves into CRAN (The Comprehensive R Archive Network), made R 1.0 publicly available 20 years ago, in 1990. I am writing these materials in Version 4.0.2.

R has a very active user community. Developers and end users have contributed more than 15,000 packages with functions and datasets that cover more academic and professional subjects that we can imagine. They range from quantitative financial analysis to astrophysics to microbiology. R has become one of the most important computer languages over the last decade, especially in the academic arena.

In universities and research institutions around the world, R is the most popular analytic research tool in use. Its presence in businesses is growing as well. In medicine, biology and microbiology, R has very important resources that come from the CRAN ecosystem and from a specialized system called Bioconductor. This latter effort has produced some 1,800 additional packages that deal with almost every important type of genomic analysis that we need for projects in biology and medicine.

One of the reasons for the strong growth of R is that it remains open-source. As such, you can acquire it without cost. It’s Free!

Why Does Professor Hunter Use R

I have a long history with programs such as SPSS, Stata, SAS, Excel and even Graphpad Prism. I began using SPSS when you still loaded your card decks with commands and data into an IBM 360 computer. (I’m speaking of the late 1960s and early 1970s.) Since then, I’ve used various versions of all of the above programs, but I was always dissatisfied. In 2011, I discovered R and understood that my dissatisfaction had a solution. The great advantage of R over the other programs is that you can completely control the sequence of operations in your analysis. You write a program (a script) and R will execute exactly what you have ordered it to do. The next day, it will produce exactly the same result as the day before when you re-run the script. You won’t have to worry about what options in a dialog box you may have selected.

Problems with the Traditional Data Analysis Programs

With all their dialog boxes and menus, the “canned” analysis programs keep you away from the details and steps of an analysis and from the intermediate results of data cleaning operations. Worse, if you do not click on exactly the same options in the same order on Tuesday that you did on Monday, the program will produce a different result. Still worse, these dialog boxes offer many options that are highly advanced and that most biologists and non-statistician researchers do not understand. As a result, the results they produce don’t make sense and can’t be explained. After all, most researchers do not understand highly sophisticated statistical reasoning, nor should they.

As Prof. Sacha Eskamp of the University of Amsterdam explained:

You can only do what the buttons say you can do. 1

Software – Open-Source vs. Comercial

As a final problem with these big programs I will discuss here, their cost is absurdly high for graduate students and for research institutions. Even the student editions of these programs are frequently beyond the means of a student. As a result, students typically make unauthorized (“cracked”) copies to access the programs. In an era when we are discussing improving the ethics of science and business, how does a student justify a career based on using stolen software?

Decades ago, open-source programs were typically of very low quality. However, no more. There exist open-source equivalents to the paid software programs in almost all areas for which we need programs. The world of open-source software has really changed the way we can do research.

R vs. Python

An alternative to R that has a somewhat similar concept for the programming of analyses is the Python language. Launched in 1991 by Guido van Rossum of the Netherlands, Python took the name of the English comedy group, “Monty Python’s Flying Circus”, not the snake species. Python is a high-level interpreted language, exactly like R. However, Python was designed as a general language in contrast to the statistical focus of R. To execute even basic statistics in Python requires learning the commands of various modules, such as Pandas and Numpy, which are necessary to load and analyze data sets in Python.

Learning R is very Difficult?

Learning the basics of R is easy. This includes learning to specify vectors and data frames and execute statistical and mathematical functions. Even in the first class, we will manage to execute various Monte Carlo simulations.2 This is a task that requires the skill of building and specifying data and carrying out an analysis.

Thus, in the initial phases of learning R, you will not suffer much. Later on, when you want to make use of more advanced packages and functions (e.g., Bioconductor), you will need to focus quite intensely to program them correctly. However, we will only approach these at the end of the course.

As with any computer language, you write commands in a format that the computer can understand, sequentially, one after the other with a syntax that appears abbreviated and unnatural, but that follows the rules of the function that you are executing. For example, if we want to find the mean of 100 random numbers between 1 and 1,000, we can say the following:

    set.seed(1)
    dados <- runif(100, min = 0, max = 1000)
    media <- mean(dados)

This example will work. (The result is 517.847.) When you install R, you can execute these commands. However, the point here is to show you that the code needs to written exactly as the program demands. As you’ve probably heard before: “a computer is a big, dumb adding machine”. It does exactly what you command it to do – and nothing else.

Installation of RStudio

Why do we need this program? RStudio gives R wings. At a basic level, RStudio provides our interface to R in the Console. It is also based on a text editor in which you can develop the scripts that you will run in R. You can best think of RStudio as the jackknife for R. You can manage files, control versions of your scripts, set up projects that keep all the files for a given task together and see your results in both reports and graphics. I will be using RStudio in all the classes of the course to control program demonstrations. All the documentation for this course have been developed in RStudio. Like R, RStudio is free. There exist commercial versions of various RStudio products but you don’t need them.

To install RStudio, navigate directly to the following page: https://www.rstudio.com/products/rstudio/download/. This will allow you avoid a lot of unnecessary commercials for their paid products.

This screen has a lot of information. You need to scroll down to a big, blue button that says, “Download RStudio for Windows” and gives the version number and size of the program. It appears similar to the following figure:

RStudio Installation

If you need additional help with the installation, I’ve put a video on my YouTube channel entitled “MAD CD Instalar R”. To reach the channel, go to: https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCbvgZ8RYeTtgjhAKE-jub5A

Starting RStudio

On your Desktop or through your menus, double click on the icon for RStudio (not the icon for R) . RStudio will open and R will automatically open within RStudio. In one of the panels (normally the panel on the left) will appear the Console. This is where R executes its functions.

On the right side of the screen will be two panels. In the upper panel, you will see various tabs. The two most important for now are the Environment (This shows variables that R its active memory.) and History (a list of commands already executed so you don’t have to retype them).

In the lower panel, there are five tabs. Files shows a directory of files in the working directory or other directory that you choose. Plots shows graphics that you create. Packages shows a list of all the R packages that you have installed on your machine. Help is a comprehensive library of all the help pages for the commands and functions that are available to you. Viewer is a mini-browser that shows reports with a high graphic content similar to web pages.

At startup, the Console will show the current version of R and provide the first caret prompt to let you know that it is loaded and ready.

RStudio Initial Screen

Install the Packages We Need

During the course, we will use various packages with additional functions that are not included in the standard initial download (“Base R”). I have prepared a script that will install packages that we will use and some that are also important adjuncts to a useful R installation. Working with this script will permit you to start learning how to use R. The script has the name: initial_packages.r.

The following is the text of the script. It’s very simple. The first command specifies a list of packages that we will install and the second calls the function install_packages() to do the work.

packages <- c("tidyverse", "broom", "car", "caret", "corrr", "data.table", 
              "descr", "devtools", "gapminder", "ggpubr", "ggvis", "ggsci", 
              "glue", "gmodels", "gt", "here", "Hmisc", "hms", "janitor", 
              "jsonlite", "kableExtra","knitr", "lattice", "lubridate", 
              "magrittr", "mice", "nortest", "nycflights13", 
              "outliers", "palmerpenguins", "pROC", "psych", "RColorBrewer", 
              "Rcpp", "readxl", "ROCR", "shiny", "styler", "summarytools", 
              "titanic", "triangle", "usethis")

#install.packages(packages)

Your First Program

In this first script, I used two important commands in R. I want to assign the name packages to the list of the 42 packages. I don’t want to have to repeat the command 42 times, once for each package. Boring. Rather, I want R to do the work. So I use the assignment operator “<-” to attribute everything on the right side of the expression to the word packages. The assignment operator consists of the left caret(Less than) symbol “<” followed by the hyphen “-”.

VSS The assignment operator is not the same as the equals sign “=”. However, R allows you to use “=” for assignment. Yes, this is confusing, but so many programmers come from an environment in which “=” means assignment that R permits it. Equality in R is a logical condition in which two values are (or are not) equal to each other. This uses a symbol composed of two equal signs (==).

My advice is to use the “<-” sign for assignment and not the “=”. Some day you will confuse the two meanings of “=”. We all do it. Develop the habit early of using “<-” for assignment and you can avoid this error.

The second command is also in the first line, the c(). This function means “combine” or “concatenate”. That is, it puts the items that follow into a vector. The items can be of any data type that R recognizes. In Chapter x, we will explore the different data types that R uses. packages is stored in memory by R as a vector. In mathematics, a vector is a one-dimensional matrix. In simple terms, it is a series of values stored as elements in a single variable. packages in our example is of type character. You will see that all the values for packages are strings and are enclosed in quotation marks. As well, the Environment tab of RStudio shows the variable packages stored with 42 values of type character (chr).

packages Vector

The second line of the script does the work. install.packages(packages) does exactly that. It goes out to CRAN’s server, downloads each package in the vector and installs it on your system.3

An important resource that we will be using in this course is GitHub. It is the public face of a version control system called git. Git allows you to maintain all the changes you make to your scripts on your computer and on the remote site GitHub. This means that you can return to a previous version of a line in a script if you discover errors in more recent versions. We will primarily be using the repository (mini-site) for the course on GitHub as a storage site for the course’s files.

But First, A Philosophical Moment

“We are drowning in information, but we are starved for knowledge”. – John Naisbitt4

Why do medicine and biology need statistics and data analysis? In medical science, the organisms we study are generally too small to be seen. Bacteria, viruses, human, animal and plant cells are too small. Even more dramatically, the machines we use to explore genetic sequences, machines that determine the frequency and location of individual nucleotides are probabilistic. “Calling bases” as a phrase, which is what the software related to sequencing does, suggests that the there can be errors. As well, the natural process of genetic replication is fraught with errors and many genomes, especially smaller genomes like those of viruses don’t have editing mechanisms to correct errors. What all this natural uncertainty means as a practical matter is that we need probabilistic means to find the underlying truth in the phenomena we study.

Also, at a clinical level, humans react to drugs, treatments, surgeries or other interventions very differently. However, we need to come to some way to sort out all these individual differences (what we call variability in statistics) to find an underlying truth.

And, that’s what statistics helps us to do. With it, we develop a set of rules and find conclusions that turns the welter of information we deal with into knowledge. While you may rely on a statistics or quantitative methods specialist to undertake advanced models and analyses you are expected, as graduate students, to be able to create at least basic analyses yourselves. And, certainly, you are expected as scientists to understand the statistics you read in papers and books, separate the wheat from the chaff, and be able to “call Bullshit”5 when someone is trying to deceive you.
